post_text: Free Grab & Go Meals Are Back! Pick up breakfast and lunch for the kids at all WVUSD schools. The USDA has announced the extension of summer meal waivers through December 31. Drive-through meal service is available weekdays for all children under 18. Elementary Schools: 11:30 a.m. – 1:10 p.m. Middle & High Schools: 7:30 a.m. – 9 a.m. and 11:30 a.m. – 1:10 p.m. Parents/guardians may pick up for all students at one location. Student does not have to be present.

August 27 at 5:35 PM ·

Tonight is Diamond Bar High School’s virtual ‘Back to School Night!’ Come to DBHS.ORG at 6:50 p.m. for a welcome message from Principal Jones and his leadership team. Please log into your google classroom tonight at 7pm and check out the videos each teacher has prepared for parents, family members, and students. This poster was designed by Studio Art student Julie Lee using Procreate on her iPad. This design is very original where the student is in monochromatic tones and the overlapping boxes reveal the true colors of the student. The Easter egg where virtual learning is happening is a nice touch. Great overall sense of dynamic contrast and unity within this art design.

post_text: Distance Learning Week #2! “They’re so cute - even through a screen!” gushed Vejar Elementary teacher Katy Schooler while helping second-grade students add speech and thought bubbles to writing assignments on Monday. Educators are making connections and developing relationships with students via Zoom classes. Students also work in virtual breakout groups and teachers meet individually to answer questions and offer suggestions. “Do you know how to draw a speech bubble?” Schooler asked one youngster. “Let’s go ahead and do it together!” she said demonstrating with a document camera. Across campus, Lauren Gullotti led her 35 fifth graders through a series of "Brain Break" stretches after the class revised their gratitude letters. “They’d typically be out running during recess time – so they need this chance to get moving!”

post_text: Great job and congratulations, Evan!
shared_text:
Diamond Bar High dbhsorg
August 7 at 11:34 PM ·

Sunday, August 2, 2020, DBHS senior Evan Thomas earned the rank of Eagle as a member of Scouts, BSA. The rank of Eagle is the highest rank that can be achieved after several years of learning skills, performing service and showing leadership within a troop. Congratulations!

Evan's Eagle Project was the construction of a fence to surround the pollinator plants in the Diamond Bar Community Garden. Evan is a member of Troop 730 in Diamond Bar.
Diamond Bar United Church of Christ Diamond Bar Community Garden Troop 730 Diamond Bar, CA

Walnut High School
July 8 at 11:27 AM ·

The 2020 IB results have been released! We are very pleased to announce that 100% of our IB students achieved either their Diploma or Career-related certificate!

To date, more than 1.2 million students worldwide have graduated from the Diploma Programme (DP) and the Career-related Programme (CP). IB students reflect diverse experiences and perspectives, attend IB World Schools in 156 countries representing an even broader range of nationalities.

Congratulations to the following 28 Walnut High School graduates on obtaining such a high honor.

post_text: It is with great sadness that we announce the passing of our friend, Ron Everett. Ron was a longtime supporter of Walnut Valley USD who settled into the community with his family over four decades ago. He was a founding member of the Walnut Valley Educational Foundation established in 1997, where he served as an Executive Board Member. He was appointed as a WVUSD Personnel Commissioner, diligently serving for 25 years until his retirement in 2018. Over the years, Ron shared kind words, a grateful handshake, and smile with hundreds of classified staff members being recognized with monthly Cornerstone Awards for exemplary service. Our deepest condolences to his wife Kay, daughter (WVUSD teacher) Marla Rickard, and the entire Everett family.

post_text:
Happy Retirement! Special Education Director Judi Koorndyk's commitment has left an imprint that has produced a positive culture and emulates All Means All. She is the type of leader that reminds us why we do what we do: take the best care of our students.

The 30-year education veteran is dedicated to improving services for children, making meaningful connections with families and staff, and always leading the Special Education department toward progress and adapting schooling for our students with unique needs.

Judi worked in developing the state-wide guide, “Transition to Adult Living: A Guide for Secondary Education,” in 2001. Her expertise and passion for Adult Transition resulted in the District’s Hockwalt Adult Resource & Transition Training (HARTT) Center, which opened in 2014, serving young adults throughout SELPA.

She has left a lasting legacy among Walnut Valley students, families, and staff!

post_text: Go Brahmas! Check out Diamond Bar High dbhsorg Marching Band members featured in the YouTube "Dear Class of 2020" production. Thank you, directors Steve Acciani and Marie Sato for providing this wonderful opportunity for our students! #Classof2020 #StrongerTogether #Covid_19
shared_text:
Diamond Bar High dbhsorg
June 7 at 2:57 PM ·

CLIP FROM YouTube's "Dear Class of 2020"

Sunday, June 7, 2020, members of Diamond Bar High's Marching Band were part of YouTube's original production "DEAR CLASS OF 2020" intended to serve as a commencement ceremony for all the high school and college students who–thanks to COVID-19–can’t attend in-person events this year.

Whenever the marching band sounds were heard, those were played by DBHS students. They also were included in several video shots as well.

The Diamond Bar High School Marching Band, the AMDA College of the Performing Arts, and the Ramón C. Cortines School of Visual and Performing Arts will perform Shawn Mendes’ “Nothing Holding Me Back”–with Mendes (another newly revealed guest) himself.

post_text:
Welcome Aboard! During the May 20 meeting, our Board of Trustees took action to approve two new administrators to the Walnut Valley team. Emiko Chapman was approved as the new Director of Special Education. Emiko is currently the Director of Special Education in the Palos Verdes Peninsula Unified School District. She has spent her entire career in Special Education, having previously served as Coordinator of Special Education and School Psychologist. She succeeds Director Judi Koorndyk, an incredible champion for students with special needs, who is retiring from her position with 21 years of service at the end of the school year.

Dr. Andrea Pomo was approved as the new Assistant Principal for Walnut High School. Dr. Poma comes to us from the Bonita Unified School District where she most recently served as Dean of Student Services. Prior to her time in Bonita, she was a high school English teacher and ELD Coordinator at West Covina High School. She earned her Doctorate from the University of Southern California. Both positions are effective July 1. Congratulations! #KidsFirst

Walnut Valley USD Virtually Celebrates 2020 Retirees! This afternoon would have been our annual Retirement Recognition Ceremony. post_text:
National Merit Scholars Announced!
Five Walnut Valley USD seniors have been named winners of prestigious 2020 National Merit Scholarships.

Congratulations to Keshav Sriram, Mena Hassan, Ryan Lou, Catherin Lu, and Tom Murickan from Diamond Bar High dbhsorg.

National Merit $2,500 Scholarship winners are the Finalists in each state judged to have the strongest combination of accomplishments, skills, and potential for success in rigorous college studies.

The high-performing students were selected based on their academic record, scores from two standardized tests, contributions and leadership in school and community activities, an essay, and a recommendation written by a high school official.

The 2,500 Merit Scholar designees were chosen from a talent pool of more than 15,000 outstanding Finalists in the 2020 National Merit Scholarship Program.

⚡️MISSION ACCOMPLISHED ⚡️

To recognize and celebrate the class of 2020, over 30 volunteers that included WHS staff, WVUSD board members, parents, the Walnut Rotary Club, and WVEF, traveled to visit the homes of 588 seniors in our 2020 graduating class. While practicing social distancing, our volunteers placed the signs on our senior's lawns as a way to honor our senior class and remind them they are missed and loved! Special shoutout to the Walnut Valley Ed. Foundation for sponsoring our students!

If your Senior did not receive one, please e-mail Shirley Markel - smarkel@wvusd.k12.ca.us. All signs were delivered to the address students have on their Aeries Student Information. Please make sure you check that address first if you changed addresses.

➡️20+ Cities

🙌 Thank you Walnut Valley Educational Foundation for purchasing the signs for our Mustangs!

post_text:
Calling Superhero Young Artists! Senator Chang invites K-6 students from Senate District 29 to participate in a COVID 19 Superhero Drawing Contest.
Create a superhero to join in the fight against coronavirus! We thank those real life heroes who fight every day to keep us safe.
Submit drawing by email to Carolina.garcia@sen.ca.gov.

Contest Rules:

- 1 entry per student

- Drawing must be superhero related

- Must be hand drawn with no stencils, templates, etc.

- Child has the choice of drawing or painting with pencil, pens, markers, colored pencils, crayons, or craft paints.

- Please include the student’s name, school, grade and parent contact information in the submission email.

- All submissions must be hand-drawn, original pieces. We will not accept artwork that uses other artists images in any way.

- The submission deadline is Wednesday, April 29

- A panel of judges will review and select the first, second, and third place winners

- Winners will be announced on Friday, May 01 and receive a special prize.

Jamie Highstreet named the Vejar Elementary Teacher of the Year! She was surprised this morning by Principal Whitney Prenger and several teachers who braved the rain and social distanced with decorated cars, signs, flowers, and cards.
"I was completely surprised. Thank you for this honor. Not only do I love teaching our students and working with families, I truly love who I teach with. I’m inspired every day by my Vejar family. I love you all ❤️" said Jamie, the school's Title 1 Program Specialist.

PBS SoCal is featuring Chaparral Middle School in an upcoming episode of the Emmy award-winning series, “Artbound.” The program will spotlight how Chaparral exemplifies arts education and how it is integrated on campus. Here are a few backstage moments from the March 11 production. Crews filmed in classrooms and interviewed 19 “expert” teachers, students, parents, and administrators.

Tuesday, March 3, 2020, was the final DB Forum led by Mrs. Sandy Davis before she retires at the end of this year!

At DB Forum students and staff experience a unique, full-day conference that explores the challenges of student stereotypes, fosters student leadership, and provides an opportunity to meet new friends. Participants get the chance to expand their understanding of themselves and others.

DB Forum is also a bonding experience in which participants have fun with their fellow students, learn about peer issues on campus, and pick up a few life skills along the way!

Thank you so much Mrs. Davis for all your years of leading our school district in SEL & Wellness! We 💜you!

post_text: WVUSD Science Olympiad Teams Score Spots at State Finals! Walnut Valley’s Science Olympiad Teams dominated the competition during the 2020 Los Angeles County Regional Finals held Saturday, February 22 at Rio Hondo College. Out of 39 middle school teams, Chaparral Middle School took 3rd Place, followed by Suzanne Middle School in 4th Place, and South Pointe Middle School in 5th Place. In the high school division among 53 competitors, Diamond Bar High dbhsorg finished with 3rd Place and Walnut High School in 4th Place. No other school district had multiple trophy-winning schools. All five schools will now prepare for the Southern California State Finals at Caltech on April 4. Congratulations to our students, coaches… and good luck at State! #WVUSDProud

February 23 at 9:12 PM · Diamond Bar, CA ·

Congratulations to DBHS junior Evan Thomas for completing his Eagle Project in the Boy Scouts of America February 23, 2020. His two-day project took place at the Diamond Bar Community Garden. It involved replacing the small wire fence that surrounded the garden of pollinator plants with a taller wooden fence and altering the entrance of the garden to improve wheel chair access. Evan is a member of Boy Scout Troop 730 in Diamond Bar, led by Scoutmaster David Chen.

post_text: Author’s Day! Child development expert and bestselling author Julia Cook delivers messages about being kind to each other, planning and setting priorities, following rules, becoming an author, problems caused by video games, being judgmental, communication, safety, and more with Evergreen Elementary students on Monday. The former teacher and school counselor has written over 100 books that let children laugh while learning to solve their own problems, use better behavior, and develop healthy relationships. “Cook’s stories about Social Emotional Learning are truly relevant and essential for our students,” said Principal Trina Dreyer. “Educators love to read her books to students because they capture their attention, offer tangible strategies, and help the adults find the words to explain difficult topics” added School Counselor Shenen Flores. Cook also hosted a parent education night and author’s day assemblies at Quail Summit Elementary.
text: Author’s Day! Child development expert and bestselling author Julia Cook delivers messages about being kind to each other, planning and setting priorities, following rules, becoming an author, problems caused by video games, being judgmental, communication, safety, and more with Evergreen Elementary students on Monday. The former teacher and school counselor has written over 100 books that let children laugh while learning to solve their own problems, use better behavior, and develop healthy relationships. “Cook’s stories about Social Emotional Learning are truly relevant and essential for our students,” said Principal Trina Dreyer. “Educators love to read her books to students because they capture their attention, offer tangible strategies, and help the adults find the words to explain difficult topics” added School Counselor Shenen Flores. Cook also hosted a parent education night and author’s day assemblies at Quail Summit Elementary.

post_text: Best L.A. County School! Congratulations to Chaparral Middle School students and coaches for an impressive finish in the 1st Annual Jeffrey Trail Science Olympiad Invitational held on Saturday at Portola High School in Irvine. "Our students continue their tradition of excellence in competition at the local, regional, and state levels,” said teacher and coach Bob Patterson.

Each sushi-rolling grad received a certificate at the end of the meal. Benihana has been a valued partner in education for over two decades. Thank you, Benihana!

post_text:
Big Winner! Tonight’s Cornerstone Awards culminate with the announcement that Louie Del Real is the 2019 Classified Employee of the Year. #WVUSDProud
Louie is a Maintenance Worker III-Locksmith in the Maintenance Operations Transportation and Facilities Division. He joined the team 19 years ago and consistently goes above and beyond all expectations. He truly cares about the wellbeing of Walnut Valley students and staff and that dedication is reflected in his quality workmanship. This talented “Jack of All Trades” craftsman can also tackle everything from carpentry, to painting, HVAC, and electrical work - and he even drives a truck. In fact, he’s even earned the nickname of “Slash” (slash-electrician, slash-carpenter, slash-truckdriver, etc.) because of his mastery of these essential skills. Louie’s a wonderful “go-to-guy” who truly puts Kids First!

shared_text:
Diamond Bar High dbhsorg
January 12 at 8:39 AM ·

Congratulations to Studio Art student Tori Kwon (12 Grader) for receiving 1st place in the 2020 Korean American Day Art Contest. Her titled piece ‘History in our Hands’, displays someone knitting iconic symbols in Korean history. This beautiful illustration was created using watercolor, ink, and pencil. Tori was formally recognized during an official award ceremony January 11, 2020 at the Korean Education Center in Los Angeles. She was awarded $100 scholarship, award plaque, and her art was published in a 2020 Korean American Day Art Calendar. Ms. Kwon’s art work was selected over 500 other entries. Please join me in congratulating this amazing accomplishment.

post_text: Walnut High Teachers Earn National Recognition! Congratulations to Walnut High teachers Diana De La Cruz and Nick Madrid who have earned the profession’s highest mark of achievement as National Board Certified Teachers (NBCTs). Only 3% of the nation’s teachers successfully pass the rigorous, performance-based, peer-review program, demonstrating their proven impact on student learning and achievement. Walnut High has a total of six active NBCT teachers (the most in WVUSD) including Jennifer Chalew, Kellee Lyons, Jennifer Maletz, Jennifer Nicolls. A total of new 3,681 NBCTs were named this month, joining more than 7,000 educators in California and 125,000 across the nation.

post_text: Get Happy! Maple Hill Elementary students celebrate Kindness Week during a high-octane assembly with Diamond Bar High alum (and classmate of Principal Kelly Morris!) Danny Vuong-Batimana. The former professional choreographer and high school teacher is now dedicated to bringing his "Happiness is Now Experience" dance parties to schools throughout the state. The proud Filipino-American shares childhood memories, entices students to step out of their comfort zone to dance, and even recruits staff members and students to perform on stage. Danny is dedicated to leaving his audiences feeling empowered, inspired, and happy!

post_text: Good Day for a Hug! South Pointe Middle School eighth grader Jordan Rivera found a way to incorporate her love of animals into her Girl Scout Silver Award project. She organized a Cuddles for Canines holiday blanket and towel drive for local animal shelters held November 14. “I just wanted to make a difference for them,” she said. In just one day, students filled three large collection boxes that will be sorted and delivered this weekend. Jordan also surprised schoolmates with a therapy dog visit during lunch. As soon as the bell rang, they flocked to the quad area to pet and love on these furry friends!

post_text: Lessons of Liberty! Walnut High students had a special opportunity to meet and learn from 18 U.S. military veterans who shared their stories of service and patriotism on November 8. The 6th annual event was organized by social studies teacher Brett Landis with support of the Armed Forces Assistance Club. “I shared that we should be grateful for our exceptional country,” said U.S. Army veteran Michael Voss. “What we have here is worth fighting for!” “All the veterans that are here pursued something bigger than themselves to support our great country,” added National Guard Recruiter Carlos Franco. #VeteransDay

post_text: Unity Day! HARTT Center made pins and collaborated with Selpa, Ron Hockwalt Academies to create a Unity tree today. While making cookies, students learned that every ingredient serves a purpose, no matter how big or small. And, once united (or mixed) we come together to make something great... or in this case super yummy! Thank you, teachers Trisha Casteneda and Marla Rickard for always putting Kids First!

post_text: WVUSD Stars Honored! The Board of Trustees paid tribute to standout students and community volunteers during the October 16 meeting. Quail Summit Elementary: 5th grader Arthy Chaisakulchai - Super Star Student Award for high scoring performances in Math Olympiad (1st place in state) and Math League (3rd place in nation). He works hard, is always kind and respectful, and helpful to classmates. Artist (and former parent) Margot Bloom - Partner in Education Award for the beautiful mural spaces she has created on campus. “Margo does all this because of her love of art and her love of Quail Summit!” said Principal Frances Weissenberger. Chaparral Middle School: 8th grader Aslin Choi - Super Star Student Award for exemplifying academic excellence (21 of 24 A+ scores!) and involvement on campus through ASB, choir, spring musical, and being a member of the UC Irvine Tech Trek Team. Volunteer Amy Hou - Partner in Education Award for dedicated work as CAPA president facilitating meetings, fundraising, and translating for the parent community. #WVUSDProud

post_text:
Organized, Efficient, Team Player! Our October Cornerstone Award recipient is John Archer, a Custodian II at Suzanne Middle School.
“John is simply amazing,” said nominator Principal Dr. Amy Smith. “He takes great pride in keeping our campus in top shape and believes that students deserve a learning environment that is safe and clean - and he makes that happen!” Each month, the Personnel Commission pays tribute to an exceptional classified employee for going above and beyond the call of duty. #BetterTogether #AboveAndBeyond
